\begin_layout Section
Discrimination of Signal and Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For multivariate classification, input variables have to be picked from
 the event kinematics.
 The choice for a certain variable is often made according to its discrimination
 power within the multivariate training phase.
 This is applicable if one is solely interested in the best background discrimin
ation with a minimum set of variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this analyses it is crucial to minimize a potential bias on the shape
 of the differential distributions after a discriminator is applied.
 This can occur if a multivariate method gets sensitive to the specific
 coupling scenario which is used for training.
 Therefore, non-correlated variables to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B,\, X}}$
\end_inset

 angles are chosen as input variables.
 This is a necessary but not a sufficient condition.
 The actual bias however is investigated by the anomalous coupling samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Choice of Independent Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way of estimating a correlation between two variables is provided by
 the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient.
 It is calculated between the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r=\frac{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)}{\sqrt{\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}}\sqrt{\sum_{i}\left(y_{i}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 are the means of the respective distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 It is only sensitive to a linear dependence between two variables.
 To detect even non-linear dependencies a more sophisticated method is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An algorithm to test an independence hypothesis has been proposed by utilizing
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-test 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "independentAlgo"

\end_inset

.
 In the following the algorithm is elaborated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be divided into two steps.
 Suppose the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are subjected to testing for independence between them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are flattened.
 This is performed by constructing a copula in which 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\rightarrow\tilde{y}$
\end_inset

 are transformed so that the distributions are only within the interval
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x},\,\tilde{y}\in[0;\,1]$
\end_inset

.
 For a finite amount 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\, y)$
\end_inset

 pairs this can be performed by sorting 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}=(x_{1},\ldots x_{N})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}=(y_{1},\ldots y_{N})$
\end_inset

 independently.
 Then each value is replaced according to its position after the sorting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{i}^{\mathrm{sorted}}\rightarrow\tilde{x}_{i}\equiv\frac{i}{N},\quad y_{i}^{\mathrm{sorted}}\rightarrow\tilde{y}_{i}\equiv\frac{i}{N}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, from the flattened distributions an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 histogram 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with equidistant binning is created.
 If the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are independent, then the histogram content is expected to be compatible
 with a two dimensional uniform distribution.
 To quantify the independence hypothesis a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-test by calculating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\frac{\left(h_{ij}-e\right)^{2}}{\sigma_{e}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the expectation value and its uncertainty for the flat hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e=\frac{N}{n^{2}},\qquad\sigma_{e}=\sqrt{\frac{N}{n^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is performed.
 The probability of this hypotheses follows a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}-(2n-1)$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 The additional 
\begin_inset Formula $2n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom are not present due to the copula transformation in
 the first step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm is feed with over 700 variables.
 This includes the transverse momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 angle, the pseudorapidity 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 and energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 of one reconstructed object.
 Additionally, more variables are calculated by choosing two particles and
 calculating their 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p_{\mathrm{T}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\eta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \Delta R=\sqrt{\Delta\eta^{2}+\Delta\phi^{2}}}$
\end_inset

, included angle, invariant mass and total transverse momentum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum p_{\mathrm{T}}^{ij}=\sqrt{\left(p_{x}^{i}+p_{x}^{j}\right)^{2}+\left(p_{y}^{i}+p_{y}^{j}\right)^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The search for independent variables to 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B.,\, X}}$
\end_inset

 is performed with the Powheg sample with about 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx55000$
\end_inset

 events.
 Each bin in the histogram 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is filled with a statistical sufficient amount of MC events of about 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx100$
\end_inset

.
 This requirement leads for the Powheg sample to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \frac{55000}{100}}\approx23^{2}$
\end_inset

 bins in 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $484$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Confidence was gained in the algorithm when it first suggested the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 angles of all particles.
 Those are expected to be independent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta_{\mathrm{B.,\, X}}$
\end_inset

 due to the detector geometry.
 But these angles do not support any discrimination power between signal
 and background processes and are therefore neglected in the variable choice.
\end_layout

