\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a true distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 leads to a measured distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)$
\end_inset

 due to smearing, finite resolution and acceptance effects.
 This can be model by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(y)=\int f(x)A(y,\, x)\mathrm{d}x\label{eq:folding-integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is called a Fredholm integral equation of the first kind 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "volkerBobel"

\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $A(y,\, x)$
\end_inset

 encodes the behavior of the detector for a transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow y$
\end_inset

 which may even include non-linear responses.
 One is then interested in solving this equation to obtain the true distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 from the measured one 
\begin_inset Formula $g(y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By discretizing the distributions within histograms, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:folding-integral"

\end_inset

 can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{y}=A\cdot\vec{x},\label{eq:unfolding}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 denotes the measured binned distribution and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 denotes the true binned distributions.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

response matrix
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and encodes the effects of the detector.
 It can be constructed through a MC simulation, where both distributions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 are accessible.
 The unfolding relies therefore on the correctness of the detector simulation.
 An element 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

 of the response matrix is proportional to the probability that a true value
 in bin 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is measured in bin 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unfolding"

\end_inset

 can simply be solved by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{x}=A^{-1}\vec{y}.\label{eq:unfolding-solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, this solution can be very unstable because unfolding is actual
 an ill-posed problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "volkerBobel"

\end_inset

.
 An example is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Oscillations"

\end_inset

.
 Starting with the true distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:true-dist"

\end_inset

 and the measured distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:measured-dist"

\end_inset

 (solid line) a response matrix is created.
 The dashed line is then subjected to unfolding by inversion of the response
 matrix.
 The result is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:oscillation-dist"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

