\end_inset

Large oscillations can appear if one tries to unfold other distributions
 with an inverted response matrix.
 Only the measured distribution which is used to construct the matrix does
 not inherited these oscillations.
 The oscillations can already arise through statistical fluctuations around
 the used measured distribution.
 To understand this behavior the singular value decomposition (SVD) provides
 more insight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SVD can be used to decompose even non-quadratic matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=U\cdot D\cdot V
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 The diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{ii}$
\end_inset

 are called singular values.
 For the unfolding problem, they are per convention normalized as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{11}=1$
\end_inset

 and sorted as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{ii}>D_{i+1,\, i+1}>0$
\end_inset

.
 To provide a simple example, the response matrix 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A=\frac{1}{2}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1+\epsilon & 1-\epsilon\\
1-\epsilon & 1+\epsilon
\end{array}\right),\qquad\epsilon\in[0;\,1]\label{eq:example-detector}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

from a fictitious detector with the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 shall be analyzed.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 goes to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 the detector can measure a variable in both bins unmistakable.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 both bins get more smeared until they are not more distinguishable by the
 detector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SVD applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 leads to the solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\vec{x} & =\underbrace{\left(U\cdot D\cdot V\right)^{-1}}_{A^{-1}}\cdot\vec{y}\\
 & =\underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)}_{=V^{-1}}\cdot\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & {\textstyle \frac{1}{\epsilon}}
\end{array}\right)}_{=D^{-1}}\cdot\underbrace{\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)}_{=U^{-1}}\cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
y_{1}\\
y_{2}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & =\underbrace{1}_{D_{11}^{-1}}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1
\end{array}\right)\cdot\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right)+\underbrace{\frac{1}{\epsilon}}_{D_{22}^{-1}}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\underbrace{\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-1
\end{array}\right)}_{\mathrm{anti\, correlation}}\cdot\left(y_{1}-y_{2}\right)\label{eq:anticorr}
\end{align}

\end_inset

for the unfolding problem.
 The last term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:anticorr"

\end_inset

 induces an negative correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If the singular value 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{22}$
\end_inset

 goes to zero, this leads to oscillations.
 The oscillation term dominates through the sorting of the singular values
 the first term involving 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{11}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:anticorr"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, this means that differences between two bins get unphysically
 amplified through a simple inversion if the response matrix contains very
 small singular values.
 For a tradeoff between unphysical fluctuations and physical meaning the
 singular values need to be regularized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regularization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple regularization method is performed by a singular value decomposition
 of the response matrix and dropping a certain amount of SVDs during the
 matrix inversion.
 This method is often called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

SVD Unfolding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The regularization can be referred to as a hard cut off which leads to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
x_{i}\rightarrow\tilde{x}_{i} & =\sum_{k}^{n}\tilde{A}_{ik}^{-1}\cdot x_{k}\\
 & =\sum_{k}^{n}\left(\sum_{j}^{\tau}V_{ij}^{-1}\frac{1}{D_{jj}}U_{jk}^{-1}\right)\cdot x_{k},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau<n$
\end_inset

 denotes the index of the smallest regarded SVD 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\tau\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 The regularized solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 inherits a bias.
 The choice of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 defines a priori the maximal curvature of the unfolded distribution.
 Therefore, regularized unfolding can only be applied if a sufficient 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 unfolded distribution is expected e.g.
 from theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This analysis uses a more sophisticated regularization method.
 The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unfolding-solution"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as the minimization of the function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{2}=\left(\vec{y}-A\vec{x}\right)^{\mathrm{T}}\cdot V_{y}^{-1}\cdot\left(\vec{y}-A\vec{x}\right)+\mathfrak{R}(\vec{x},\,\vec{y}),\label{eq:chi2-unfolding}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}$
\end_inset

 denotes the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tunfold"

\end_inset

.
 If the measured distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 contains no correlations between its entries the covariance matrix can
 be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y,\, jj}=\sqrt{y_{j}}$
\end_inset

 which assumes Poisson uncertainties.
 The optional term 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathfrak{R}(\vec{x},\,\vec{y})=\tau^{2}\vec{x}\cdot L^{\mathrm{T}}L\cdot\vec{x}+\left(\sum y_{i}-\epsilon^{\mathrm{T}}\vec{x}\right)\label{eq:reg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is added to suppress large fluctuations.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 approximates numerically the second derivatives from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
 It utilizes the general formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2}f(x)}{\mathrm{d}x^{2}}\approx\frac{x_{i+1}-2\cdot x_{i}+x_{i-1}}{h^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for the second derivative of a discretizing generic function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 with the step width 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
checkthis{ref to numerical recipies?)}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Additionally, the second term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:reg"

\end_inset

 invokes a constrain on the total number of events in the unfolded distribution
 by using the diagonal efficiency matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by minimizing equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chi2-unfolding"

\end_inset

 the additional term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{R}$
\end_inset

 suppresses solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 with large curvatures and corrects simultaneously for acceptance effects.
 Oscillating solutions have high curvatures and are therefore rejected.
 The regularization parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 controls the influence of the second derivatives in the minimization and
 has to be chosen carefully.
 If it is chosen too small, unphysical oscillations are not sufficient suppresse
d.
 But if it is chosen too large, the solution is biased towards a solution
 with the smallest curvature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This regularization method is special case of the Tikhonov-Phillips regularizati
on.
 
