\begin_layout Standard
In this analysis the optimal value of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is estimated by investigating the correlations in the unfolded solution.
 The procedure is demonstrated for a similar detector given in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:example-detector"

\end_inset

 which has been extended to measure in four different bins.
 The resulting correlations in the unfolded distribution can be calculated
 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}$
\end_inset

 of the unfolded distribution is obtained by propagation of uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{x}=J\cdot V_{y}\cdot J^{\mathrm{T}}=\tilde{A}^{-1}\cdot V_{y}\cdot\left(\tilde{A}^{-1}\right)^{\mathrm{T}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the regularized inverted response matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the correlation between two bins 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{ij}=\frac{\mathrm{cov}_{ij}}{\sqrt{\mathrm{var}_{i}\cdot\mathrm{var}_{j}}}=\frac{V_{x,\, ij}}{\sqrt{V_{x,\, ii}\cdot V_{x,\, jj}}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For analysis, the correlations coefficients are average as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
"\langle\rho_{i,i+j}\rangle"\equiv\frac{1}{n-j-1}\cdot\sum_{i}^{n-j-1}\rho_{i,i+j}.
\]

\end_inset

Then, negative correlations between directly adjacent bins leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\rho_{i,i+1}\rangle<0$
\end_inset

